answers.body:
Only add a border <code>:before</code> , using sibling selectors. Then give an <code>:after</code> border to the <code>:last-child</code>    <code>.mark-borders:before,
.mark-borders + .mark-borders:before,
.mark-borders:last-child:after
{
  content: '';
  display: block;
  position: absolute;
  height: 0;
  width: 100%;
  margin-top: -1px;
  border-bottom: dashed 1px #ccc;
}
.mark-borders:hover:before,
.mark-borders:hover + .mark-borders:before,
.mark-borders:last-child:hover:after
{
  border-bottom: solid 1px red;
  z-index: 1;
}</code>  <code><div>
  <div class="mark-borders">
    <h1>
      Hello
    </h1>
  </div>
  <div class="mark-borders">
    <p>
      Some content
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="mark-borders">
    <h1>
      World
    </h1>
  </div>
</div></code>

Ive edited your code and came up with this: https://jsfiddle.net/7g31c5rp/4/  <code>.mark-borders:nth-of-type(2):after,
  p.mark-borders:after{
  display: none;
}
.mark-borders:hover + .mark-borders:before{
   border-bottom: solid 1px red;
   z-index: 1;
}
</code>  removing the some-content after and targeting the WORLD before on hover.

